## ğŸ“Œ What is Persistent Disk (PD)?  
- Persistent Disk is a **durable block storage solution** provided by Google Cloud.  
- It can be **attached to VM instances** and behaves like a physical hard drive.  
- Data persists even after VM stops or restarts.  

---

## ğŸ”‘ Key Features  
- **Durable & Reliable** â€“ Data is replicated across multiple locations within a zone.  
- **Scalable** â€“ Resize disks without downtime.  
- **Types of Persistent Disks**:  
  - Standard PD (HDD) â€“ cost-effective, good for sequential access.  
  - SSD PD â€“ high performance, low latency.  
  - Extreme PD â€“ very high IOPS, for specialized workloads.  
- **Regional PD** â€“ Replicated across two zones in the same region for high availability.  

---

## âš™ï¸ Use Cases  
- Running databases (needs reliable block storage).  
- Applications requiring **consistent & fast I/O performance**.  
- Backup & restore operations.  

---

## ğŸ”„ Snapshots & Backups  
- Persistent Disks support **snapshots** for backups.  
- Snapshots are **incremental** â€“ only changes are saved, reducing cost.  
- Snapshots can be used to create **new disks** quickly.  

---

## ğŸ” Security  
- All Persistent Disks are **encrypted by default**.  
- Users can also provide their own **encryption keys (CMEK)**.  

